            </title>. Yale Collection of Western Americana, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <processinfo id="aspace_de8faad2f1f6c60651f808ee6093453f">
         <head>Processing Notes</head>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit. These materials have been arranged and described according to national and local standards. For more information, please refer to the Beinecke Manuscript Unit Processing Manual.</p>
         <p>Each folder in the collection contains a single inkjet print.</p>
      </processinfo>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_9d056381e50512d1d06ee140db634d70">
         <head>Description of Papers</head>
         <p>Collection of fourteen composite photographs of skies and sites at Marfa, Texas, created by Karen Halverson in 2017 and printed as color inkjet prints on Canson Platine Fibre Rag Paper, 24.25 x 33 inches (62 x 84 centimeters).</p>
         <p>The inkjet prints each have a 5:7 image ratio that presents composite images consisting of two or three discrete images. All the prints include a view of the sky at Marfa, Texas, with a 2:3 image ratio positioned over a view of a surface at Marfa, including grasslands, roads, and paved surfaces, with an image ratio of approximately 2:15. Many prints include a third smaller image that documents a detail of a building, vegetation, or signs at Marfa positioned between the views of the sky and surface.</p>
         <p>The prints are untitled with parenthetical numbers provided by Halverson to differentiate images.</p>
         <p>The collection comprises an edition numbered three of ten.</p>
         <p>Prints signed and with manuscript identifications on versos.</p>
      </scopecontent>
